import React, { Component } from 'react'; import Container from 'react-bootstrap/Container'; import Row from 'react-bootstrap/Row'; import Col from 'react-bootstrap/Col'; import Table from 'react-bootstrap/Table'; import Button from 'react-bootstrap/Button'; import Collapse from 'react-bootstrap/Collapse'; /*import { Document } from 'react-pdf'; import { pdfjs } from 'react-pdf'; import resume from '../../imgs/resume.pdf'; pdfjs.GlobalWorkerOptions.workerSrc = `//cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/pdf.js/${pdfjs.version}/pdf.worker.js`; */ class ExperienceContainer extends Component { constructor(props) { super(props); this.state = { pyOpen: false, cOpen: false, cppOpen: false, csOpen: false, jsOpen: false, swiftOpen: false, reactOpen: false, } } render() { return (

Technical Experience

This page will outline and display various techical projects and experiences I have taken part in. You can also download my resume here.

Programming Languages

this.setState({pyOpen: !this.state.pyOpen})} aria-controls="py-collapse-text" aria-expanded={this.state.pyOpen} style={dropDownButton}>

Python
I have taught this language, used extensively with many different frameworks for both projects and competitive programming. Most comfortable language.
this.setState({cOpen: !this.state.cOpen})} aria-controls="c-collapse-text" aria-expanded={this.state.cOpen} style={dropDownButton}>

C
Not my favorite language, but I have used it extensively as it was the main language used in curriculum during my education. I have used this language in a wide variety of contexts, such as embedded systems, networking, security, and many more.
this.setState({cppOpen: !this.state.cppOpen})} aria-controls="cpp-collapse-text" aria-expanded={this.state.cppOpen} style={dropDownButton}>

C++
Another language I used extensively in school, as it was the second most common language in my coursework (used to teach OOP concepts). I have done many projects in this language from computational biology to distributed systems. One of my future goals is to learn modern C++, as this was never covered during my education.
this.setState({csOpen: !this.state.csOpen})} aria-controls="cs-collapse-text" aria-expanded={this.state.csOpen} style={dropDownButton}>

C#
I have used C# quite a bit, but not in a lot of contexts. I primarily used it for game programming with Unity. I enjoy using it, and I feel that it would be easy for me to transfer knowledge of the language to different types of work besides game programming in the future.
this.setState({jsOpen: !this.state.jsOpen})} aria-controls="js-collapse-text" aria-expanded={this.state.jsOpen} style={dropDownButton}>

Vanilla JavaScript
I have used vanilla JS quite a lot this past year to make quick web pages and games. Although I have used it a lot, I feel that my knowledge is lacking in front-end development and all of the code I have wrote was not the highest quality. I most likely will only use vanilla JS in the future for fun in quick projects.
this.setState({swiftOpen: !this.state.swiftOpen})} aria-controls="swift-collapse-text" aria-expanded={this.state.swiftOpen} style={dropDownButton}>

Swift 4
Similar to vanilla JS, I have used it quite a lot in the past year for making quick mobile apps. I find it quite fun working in the Swift ecosystem, but I do not know exactly what it takes to write high quality Swift code. I hope to improve my Swift skills in the future if I find myself working on an iOS focused project, as mobile app development interests me quite a bit.
this.setState({reactOpen: !this.state.reactOpen})} aria-controls="react-collapse-text" aria-expanded={this.state.reactOpen} style={dropDownButton}>

React JavaScript
Similar to vanilla JS, I have used it quite a lot in the past year for making quick mobile apps. I find it quite fun working in the Swift ecosystem, but I do not know exactly what it takes to write high quality Swift code. I hope to improve my Swift skills in the future if I find myself working on an iOS focused project, as mobile app development interests me quite a bit.
